rose and the lighthouse ~~ this good morning in brother’s hand~me~down chestnut leather boots and beloved birthday cake hat.🥀she is all "hewe, mama" passing me lovely stones and every dog is beautiful, every dog is "awchie." she presents her hand and wishes you (anyone) to kiss it and erupts in a fit of giggles when you do. she almost always has a dollie or three or two palmfuls of mice or her spelt~tummied warming goose the size of her in tow, and she loves SHOES (and 🥀 will🥀 tell 🥀 you) especially the ones with mary jane straps and especially the ones with mary jane straps and GLITTER. if she sees you making anything in the kitchen at all she will 🥀gasp🥀 and run to pull out plates (enough for everyone) which reminds me sososo much of her brother at this age. she is utterly my shadow, my roseshadow, i am nowhere without her at my hem (of my dress, of my very soul). there is no boundary where the country of her begins and i end ~ only shared soil, only what time has made, and made again. 🥀🥀

a candle lit, a beacon aflame in every corner of the winterhouse. "little lighthouses" i whisper to my beautiful husband, behind the dark curtain of his locks. and then, only this, no other ambition than to seashell my motherlimbs around their bodies, only as small as they will ever be. 🥀sometimes i lay the children to moonkeeping and rise to children standing taller by my thighs by sunrise, their cotton pajamas hilariously, heartbreakingly highwatered in hours. and i read up on it ~~ and tis not my imagination, but the natural way of things. my god. it feels truer than memoir, how: sometimes not at all, then everything allatonce.🥀 "don’t blink" they say. everyone in the market queue, every grandmother on every walk and nurse and postman, it’s like a cresting wave of utterance that they literally cannot stop themselves from opening their mouths to unfurl. but. i say, look. look really really long and well and breathlessly, tenderly, suffer with your doting eyes the wonderful shape of their smallness that feels sacred, infinite and impossibly brief at once and then do it: blink. because you can’t not. you have to blink as much as their bodies have to masterfully uncoil and elongate inches by hours. you couldn’t stop it if you tried, as much as you can’t stop the tides or request the moon keep its lovely crescent shape another few nights. it’s true; it’s so true that you will shiver with the truth of it, that you can’t enter some rooms of their childhoods again, not really, even though they are there, seashelled within their nows. you won’t touch the walls of the memoryrooms of when they were one or two, or sniff their lovely soft crowns or cradle their peony cheeks and maybe like me you wake in the night your heart exploding out of your chest at the thought of it ~~ there will be a last time he asks for his basket "just to pick some bewwies while i wait for you." but all the better to keep it on ~~ the too~fleeting carousel of it: look / blink / look / blink. there will always be something to see and blinking eyes will see it better. and every shape of the ocean and the moon was so lovely anyhow. (and so too, highwaters.) 🌊🥀

sometimes ~~ i wake with the bell~heart clang of it ~~ how the shapes of him at one breath or two years or three, the silky whispiness of his locks and the sweetness of utterances ~ "mama, whadt ift we just cwuddle and be so cozy and watcht some puffin wock?" and "cha~cha motts" for chocolate milk feel like rooms i can’t enter again (not really, i mean, not with my prayerpalms, virginmother ears, not with my lovely right~here senses). not like 🥀that.🥀 i mean sometimes i wake in the night feeling like i am searching for a door~key. the memory of him intoning "cidery acckles" ~~ (apples) is etched indelibly in my mother~memory like "in god we trust" to a silver coin plunked in a lake with a wish. i think sometimes i feel very deeply the ache that i won’t sit across a certain shape of my sweet son at the dinner table. this is simply true. it is also simply true that ah~there~he~is in the chipped rose plate repaired with slivershimmers of gold. i mean: his wobbly birdsong of three won’t wash on the shores of me again in just that way ~~ but it also true ~~ my god ~~ the rooms have windows. and the rooms seashell around the rooms like years rosied around years and he is too large, too promising, too heavenly for a single room; my son, a castle. and maybe in the night when the heart~clangs come, i can say "ah there you are" because there he was ~ visiting my dreams. and doesn’t he visit his own? when he rises in the good dawn of his birthday~fifth and croons to his primrose "hellooo my sweet~eee" and "sweetie" is two syllables equally weighted and lands more like "sweet tea" isn’t "cha~cha motts" right there, isn’t it right up against this new good shape, don’t they know each other like a family of birds? i don’t know, but i cling to it like grace. here, i yoke my soul to silky, lengthy life, to hims and hims and hims (to hymns and hymns and hymns). 🥀

my grammy therese departed at 12:12 under the moon of thursday and i was with her (beautiful her) ~ and my mother, my aunt, her so~loved daughters. i am (we are) seashaken, sunk like a stone at the colossal loss of her. i brushed her hair with the wooden baby brush i bought her and tucked poesy’s baby blankie around her and my mother sang to her and we touched her silverswan hair and found her soft palms and i felt in that moment therese as a small girl was so, so near, and so i brushed her hair and called her: so pretty, so good, so beloved. i told her ~ i love being your granddaughter. i told her every good and beautiful thing in my life was because of her. 🥀 when i was small and my grammy came into town without fail her first act was to corral some combination of my five brothers and me, wildlings, ferret us to costco for a bounty of food. one of the last things she gave me was from costco~ two blue puffer coats for my son and daughter in sizes they are still blossoming into (i think: she will keep them warm winters beyond This Winter). then, she’d get a big costco pizza for home and immediately set to pruning a tree or tightening a bolt ~ she had a subscription to Popular Mechanics. she had a brightness to her voice when she walked through the door crooning "hiiiiiii!" and her laugh and her eyes and the way she moved her body joyously through the good and sometimes painful work of living. i was thinking how her body had its own tangles, like any of us do. how she carried her own anxieties and preoccupations and sadnesses and longings and loveheld hopes and affections and little~big joys ~~~ how, like for any of us, they rose in her body, in tummy~knots or unstill palms or heart thrums. and what is also true is how she moved her body. her bright, beautiful busyness. an act of holiness. wasn’t she always praying? (fixing the sink, mowing the wide lawn with her arm in a sling, tossing a ball, gathering the scattered leaves, holding a child.) she was so Here. and maybe the way she lived was also her Instructions in How To Miss Her. how to try to do the impossible work of that. 🥀 we were (we are) so lucky to have been mothered, been loved, by you.

our palms smell of fruit and june (strawberries rain~gathered in the garden, their rouge skins so bright they could be glass), rufus wainwright sunspins in our air, our hair wet from morning showers and not~dry by sundown, sweet~sweet rainier cherries, berry and chocolate stains on white dresses, radishes with salted butter and flaky salt, we believe the sea softens all so we furl to it, cast out to it, he and i and the children, and cups of coffee and old baskets fill with shells and the shells fill jars and shelves and cubbies and bowls and beeswax fills the shells and firelight fills the wick in the beeswax in the shells from the sea. and the story is — the story always is — light, light, light.

just in from moonclipping roses, saturday night. summer’s a slipstream a sistergowns, slipped silklike, selkielike over unmentionables. freshening the water by the light of the moon. i will wash my feet in the sink. someone (new) comes for a playdate in the morning and this has happened countless times now but the thought of it always makes my stomach twist and so i just breathe and brush my daughter’s hair out of her eyes and i am so swept to the~here, to the everything~ness of this ~~~ that if i don’t fit neatly in the margins of being easily knowable or good at conversation or creating the home whose magic can be read in other hearts ~~ i have her. "i have my beautiful daughter.” almost every morning is cool enough for a fire. i wait for monday’s mail, two gowns (white) and a parcel of tiny paint pots from theeeee 🥀farrow & ball🥀~~ the sweet~suite (suite~sweet) of pinks, what else. 🥀chandelier in shape~poem of empire~french. we are around & around & around how to paper or paint the littleloft room~theirs ~~ reference points are dakota johnson’s persuasion ~~ also the room sebastian’s wife succumbs to sickness to in anne w an e. what can i say, i am who i am (and who i am and who i am).

a good monday / my years~longed~for sample pots for front~o~the~house ~~ for a hearthkeep room, a library, have arrived. and they are ballet slippers, english rose gardens, all. 🥀💅🏽🕯"my girls" i intone, slipping them from a porch~swept parcel ~~ and beside me, my daughter stacks them like lovely seaslipped stones, "o peeetttyyyy" she says. when the pots are spent they will be water~dips for her watercolors (and the room all around her, blushing).🥀

the way she calls all books ~ "storybooks." the way she packs her burgundy velvet knapsack for any outing, no matter how brief. the way she dances to taylor swift’s "august." the way she wants to play 🥀giving a haircut🥀 and pulls up her own thimblesmall child’s chair in french grey for you and how she brushes your hair and gives your shoulder a squeeze ~~ and announces ~~ "alllll done! you cute! lookt in miwwowr!" 🥀

just catching up on our lil photo journal here 🩰 here’s me & poesy at the library on a rainy september morning. rose’s current obsessions are ~~~ angelina ballerina, booooooks (she always has, like, five under her arm (same)), everything elsa, baby dolls, and her ballerina bunny rabbit named "bop." she likes to play "happy birthday" which is a game where i light so many taper candles and she sings the birthday song and blows them out & she likes to pretend she is giving haircuts and at the end she nudges you to a mirror and announces, "you all done! you so cute!" she is my roseshadow, my evernear, and whenever i swap the pillowcases or set out a tablecloth she gasps and rubs her cheek against it snd squeals "is sooooo pwetty, mama. ank~soo!" and often she will stamp her little feet in cheerful exuberance ~ leading her own parade. 🥀 she always has stuff with her. like ~ books, socks, stuffies, cleaning supplies, a plate she finds pretty, a candelabra, etc. the only thing i can think of that she really has a distaste for is pants. she’s so so so joyful and she is always humming and singing and dancing and flitting and floating and we are just really so (very) in love with her. 🩰🥀

for sennight now, primrose swan moonrises to gather the four cardinal points of her pillow two~by~two in her thimblesmall palms to smooth them, and presses in the feather~belly of its center, re~fluffing it as if by sleepwalking, dreamdance. watching her holy~work of it in the sparkling dark, is like witnessing sacrament. as if she is so beholden to some orbit that her body fathoms slipping off the earth if she doesn’t do it. like essentiality. like essence. she has so many tender must~be~just~so’s. i could tether my soul to the ship of her everywhichways and would and i do and i promise to be saved by it. there are one thousand instances. the leaning stack of books whose titles she transposes like magic. she gathers my hands and notes the fingertips, whispering the figure to herself twice, then nodding in prayerful confirmation. the circling of the bed in search of feathers. a girl so kept by some conviction, by some unseeable gravity. i thumb through my own museum of musts/ors, like masts/oars that keep my ship afloat. and i see it, i see it all and all at once, like a murmuration of starlings: one thousand wingbeats a second, the safe, safe shape of it. 🦢

years~on, what would we say of it? of this first week of november, of any of it? wouldn’t it always be this way: that mom kept stock of the days by who was sent away for (tiny velvet rosevined shoes, so many books) ~ ~ what we gathered (so many dvds ~ and all for a song, fresh wellies, the miracle of a last~to~be~gathered mary oliver (which i have never ever found at a thrift) and tucked just beside wendell berry besides!), who was read (the book of goose, my wife said you may want to marry me, tom lake, everyday sacred) ~ our wheres (we were so sick ~ the schoolhouse sometimes, but mostly we made countries of each other’s arms, in the footlands of the fireplace), what we feasted on (grapefruit, the flaky~salt freezer peanut butter cups we made, cans of white beans in rivers of olive oil and sage), our neglects (the wifi switched off to watch one by one the (so many) dvds), our prayers (the twin flames of despair & thanksgiving; how we did light two tapers for each), our joys (clear scans, each other) what we would name miracles (all the aforementioned everythings). our joys, our memorykeeps, what would always be ours, our november~sweet. 🥀

it is so cold this morning. tonight we will burn wood in the hearth and don wool indoors and all day i will wait to hear the click of the upstairs hot~vent clicking to life, how you feel instantly warmed just from the click of it before any air is given. we gather him from early release at the schoolhouse and take him for lunch and the playground and his heart’s deepest wish: ornaments for the tree. to occupy the holy~seat of the passenger side on a near~winter drive is a lovesong of mountains of mittens and child~size coats, of softworn unicorns (for my daughter, from my son (this is, itself, a poem)), and ballerina dresses for the daughter too, and paperbacks of yiyun li, and it is the way my daughter hums along to hisoyakani by lamp and she doesn’t miss a note. 🎻 my novemberkeeps (only some of).

it is the eve’s eve of thanksgiving. last night my husband was a vision softstepping through the door with the frigid air ribboning in the doors behind, so thick with cold that it was visible, like plumes of silversmoke, and his arms spilling over with our every need ~~ sacks of cranberries and a feast of oranges and honeycrisps and garlic and potatoes golden and sweet and sage and cider that sparkles, heavy cream and satchels of glittering sugar and so much irish butter, and brie and black tea and bourbon and stout and maple and spools and spoils or velveteen ribbon in bleu, in noir. and after he has returned with it all he pulls my shopping lists from his topcoat pockets and pins them to fridge saying "they’re beautiful” saying "safekeeping." he even returns with a tiny leather football tucked under his arm in "pee~wee" size because i don’t know of or care for the sport in the least but i have always wanted it like this: after supper, tucked in 90s crewneck sweaters and cardigans and baseball hats and mittens, tossing the ball on the lawn like they do in dan in real life or like rufus humphrey takes his children to do in gossip girl. (like we did once, In Another Year, when the dog caught the ball and pierced it with his sharp teeth. 🥀). and this morning, my daughter is two and within one minute of waking she asks to start a fire. and there are coats strewn all over the front room while i wait for more hooks. the fire roars this good morning. and i think (as i think a thousand times an hour) ~ how i want to be like my daughter. how i want to rise, and make light. 🥀🗝

thanksgiving eve 🥀🗝 "i get to be a mom on thanksgiving" ~~ the lovesong that never, ever stops. the lovesong that only grows. 🥀 a morning of sore throats ~~ of fireplace cuddles and same~cloth jammies and paddington and little women and buttery pie crusts palm~pressed with sparkling sugar and scraped vanilla beans and candlelight (always) and milksong respites up up up in the loft, and a favorite cup, and the ceremonial choosing of The Cranberry Spoon.🥀 i wonder if someday i will look back on all of this ~ of rising with a thrum in my throat and pressing into it the only way i know how ~ with a bottomless drip of coffee and black tea, and all~morn cinema and an everlasting fire in the hearth, browning butter on the stovetop with one hand and pouring eggnog for my precious two~year~old daughter with the other ~ i wonder if someday it will all feel a dream. doesn’t it, even this hour? i wonder where, when i someday silverswaned and the hours are quieter, i will hold it all, and i am broken, sunk to it, sunk and shored to knowing i cannot, i never could, i could only sing it. (i mean: thank you; thank you; thank you.) 🎻

saturday morning in The January House. at the table, the dog begs for scraps; he knows to go to the daughter. i write down primrose swan’s mixtape from the winter when she was two (what she asks for; what is always changing; everything). there is a broken pane of glass in the french door, covered with a rose print. i make a coffee, and i hear him from two rooms beyond me, strumming his black les paul. i am thinking again about my theory about The Infinity Of Echoes. 🥀

a sweetspent sunday morning ~ coffee, tea, and milk in clinky blue cups, playing with the children, finishing "the covenant of water." it is a sunday in january, and my only ambition for its hours is this, which is ink~penned to my journal ~ "enjoying light." ✨
